{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16299"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116106"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8990"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"},{"type":"tags","id":"10455"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21390"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116106"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary auditory pathway processes sound information as it travels from the cochlea through various brainstem nuclei to reach the auditory cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the brainstem nucleus that receives bilateral projections from the cochlear nuclei along with the inferior colliculus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial geniculate nucleus","Medial vestibular nucleus","Superior olivary complex","Medial longitudinal fasciculus","Inferior olivary nucleus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior olivary complex\u003C/strong\u003E and inferior colliculus both receive bilateral projections from the cochlear nuclei. The superior olivary complex is particularly important for sound localisation by comparing timing and intensity differences between the two ears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial geniculate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is a thalamic relay nucleus that receives input from the inferior colliculus, not directly from cochlear nuclei. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial vestibular nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in balance and eye movements, not auditory processing. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial longitudinal fasciculus\u003C/strong\u003E is a fibre tract involved in eye movement coordination, not an auditory nucleus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior olivary nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in cerebellar function, not auditory processing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter processing in the superior olivary complex and inferior colliculus, auditory information proceeds to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus and then to the primary auditory cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary auditory pathway includes bilateral projections from cochlear nuclei to both the superior olive and inferior colliculus.","The superior olive is important for sound localisation through comparison of inputs from both ears.","After the superior olive and inferior colliculus, auditory information proceeds to the medial geniculate nucleus and then primary auditory cortex."],"references":["Rubio ME. Auditory brainstem development and plasticity. Curr Opin Physiol. 2020 Dec;18:7-10. doi: 10.1016/j.cophys.2020.07.002. Epub 2020 Jul 7. PMID: 33103017; PMCID: PMC7583349.","Deep NL, Choudhury B, Roland JT Jr. Auditory Brainstem Implantation: An Overview. J Neurol Surg B Skull Base. 2019 Apr;80(2):203-208. doi: 10.1055/s-0039-1679891. Epub 2019 Feb 14. PMID: 30931229; PMCID: PMC6438789.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T14:57:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T14:59:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8990"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116106"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"